---
import Layout from "../../layouts/Layout.astro";
import srcImage from "../../assets/best-bass-fishing-spots-medford-oregon.png";
import { Image } from "astro:assets";
import MyH1 from "../../components/MyH1.astro";
import Bests from "../../components/Bests.astro";
---
<Layout 
title="Best bass fishing spots near Medford, Oregon"
description="Comprehensive guide to the best bass fishing hotspots – with seasonal tips, gear suggestions, and local insights."
url="https://medford.oregonfishingforum.com/bass/best-spots/"
type="article"
site_name="Oregon Fishing Forum"
ogimage={srcImage.src}
>
    <div class="text-center">
			<MyH1 text="Best bass fishing spots near Medford, Oregon" />
			<p class="mb-4">Comprehensive guide to the best bass fishing hotspots – with seasonal tips, gear suggestions, and local insights.</p>

			<Image
				src={srcImage}
				alt="Best bass fishing spots near Medford, Oregon"
                width={1344}
                height={768}
				loading={"eager"}
				fetchpriority={"high"}
                layout='constrained'
                class="rounded-xl shadow mx-auto"
				/>
				<br>
    </div>


<h3>
    <strong>1. Emigrant Lake (aka Emigrant Reservoir)</strong>
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        5 miles south of Ashland, ~20 miles from Medford 
    </li>
    <li>
        Excellent for both <strong>smallmouth and largemouth bass</strong>; spring spawning draws them into shallow arms, evenings and early mornings offer great topwater action
    </li>
    <li>
        Good bank access from Songer Wayside and the County Park; a boat helps reach deep drop-offs near the dam
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    <strong>2. Lost Creek Lake (Reservoir)</strong>
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        Located ~27 miles northeast of Medford 
    </li>
    <li>
        Known for <strong>smallmouth bass fishing</strong> along dam and rocky outcrops; largemouth use coves and willow-covered shoals 
    </li>
    <li>
        Excellent access via Joseph H. Stewart State Recreation Area (ramps and marina)
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    <strong>3. Howard Prairie Lake &amp; Hyatt Lake</strong>
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        Howard Prairie (~37 miles east) &amp; Hyatt (~23 miles east) are stocked lakes with <strong>large populations of largemouth and smallmouth bass</strong>, plus trout
    </li>
    <li>
        Boat ramps available; coves, inlets, and rocky shoreline ideal for bank and kayak anglers
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    <strong>4. Applegate Lake</strong>
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        ~27 miles southwest of Medford 
    </li>
    <li>
        Holds <strong>abundant smallmouth bass</strong>, along with largemouths; Squaw and Carberry Creek arms are hotspots
    </li>
    <li>
        Shore access near dam and creek arms; no‑wake rules make kayak fishing very appealing&nbsp;
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    <strong>5. Agate Lake</strong>
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        ~13 miles northeast of Medford
    </li>
    <li>
        A smaller, warmer reservoir that gets stocked with bass; good shoreline access along willow- and cattail-lined banks
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    <strong>6. Phoenix Canal</strong>
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        Located in Jackson County near Phoenix—ideal for <strong>bank fishing</strong> 
    </li>
    <li>
        Known for <strong>spotted and largemouth bass</strong>, as well as bluegill and smallmouth; easy access and family-friendly
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    <strong>7. Expo and Medco Ponds (Urban Options)</strong>
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        Expo Pond at Jackson County Fairgrounds (~5 minutes away) and Medco Pond (~40 miles away) stocked with bass, bluegill, and trout 
    </li>
    <li>
        Great for beginners and families—easy shore access and reliable catches
    </li>
</ul>
<h2>
    Seasonal and Tactical Summary
</h2>
<figure class="table">
    <table>
        <thead>
            <tr>
                <th>
                    <strong>Location</strong>
                </th>
                <th>
                    <strong>Best Season</strong>
                </th>
                <th>
                    <strong>Techniques</strong>
                </th>
            </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
            <tr>
                <td>
                    Emigrant Lake
                </td>
                <td>
                    Spring (shallows), Summer mornings/evens
                </td>
                <td>
                    Spinners, jigs, soft plastics for structure &amp; drop-offs
                </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>
                    Lost Creek Lake
                </td>
                <td>
                    Year-round, peak spring/summer
                </td>
                <td>
                    Spinnerbaits, jigs near dam, rocky shoreline, boat access ideal
                </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>
                    Howard Prairie / Hyatt
                </td>
                <td>
                    Spring/fall post-stocking
                </td>
                <td>
                    Crankbaits, creature baits in coves and inlets
                </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>
                    Applegate Lake
                </td>
                <td>
                    Spring &amp; summer
                </td>
                <td>
                    Tube jigs, worms in creek arms; kayak for deep water
                </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>
                    Agate Lake
                </td>
                <td>
                    Spring through fall
                </td>
                <td>
                    Topwater plugs early/late, plastics in cattails
                </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>
                    Phoenix Canal
                </td>
                <td>
                    Summer months
                </td>
                <td>
                    Small plastics, spinners, NATURAL baits
                </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>
                    Expo / Medco Pond
                </td>
                <td>
                    Spring &amp; warm months
                </td>
                <td>
                    PowerBait, worms under bobbers—easy family fun
                </td>
            </tr>
        </tbody>
    </table>
</figure>
<h2>
    Quick Start Tips
</h2>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Gear Suggestions</strong>: Medium-heavy rod, 10–15 lb test line, tube jigs, spinners, rubber worms
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Top colors</strong>: Gold, black, chartreuse, natural greens/browns
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Boats/Kayaks</strong>: Strongly recommended for Emigrant, Lost Creek, Applegate—shore anglers do fine in Agate and canals
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Family-friendly</strong>: Expo/Medco ponds and Phoenix Canal offer reliable, stress-free fishing
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Regulations</strong>: Follow ODFW rules (bag limits, bait restrictions, water advisories)
    </li>
</ul>

<Bests bestFor="bass" />
</Layout>